N2 absorption-desorption isotherms of all three samples (Fig. 3
                        ) showed type IV isotherms, indicating the presence of mesoporous structures on their surfaces [45]. The increased specific surface area of P-CN/BC (19.28 m2g-1 to 57.93 m2g-1) was attributed to the presence of biochar BC (Fig. S5), which prevented excessive accumulation of P-CN [40]. The specific surface area of P-CN/BC/NCDs was further increased to 79.36 m2g-1, indicating a rougher specific surface area (Table 1
                        ). The higher proportion of porous structure would provide more active sites for the catalytic reaction, which was consistent with the SEM results [43]. The increased pore size and pore volume of P-CN/BC imply improved adsorption capacity. The significantly higher photocatalytic efficiency of P-CN/BC/NCDs compared to P-CN/BC suggested that the introduction of NCDs enhanced the electronic structure and interfacial electron transfer ability of P-CN/BC.
